Earlier this semester I attended a SASC meeting. It was my first time attending such a meeting, which may or may not be a surprise since I do not identify ethnically as South East Asian (if so, surprise!). On the other hand, as a physics major who is really not at all politicized, I have spent a considerable amount of time in API-progressive spaces over the last several years (for various reasons) despite having little reason to do so, and yet last week's meeting was different.

&nbsp;

It was different because when we were split up into small groups for an activity, two of the other students in my group were of mixed heritage. One was half Chicano, while the other was half Black. Surely this could be abnormal simply given the context of the meeting, but it was especially different for me. As someone who is mixed, I oftentimes find myself underrepresented even in communities that call for greater representation. I rarely feel that special sense that others in these spaces feel, that sense of belonging, the sense that they are part of a greater community even as they fight for more presence in greater society. That's not necessarily a bad thing. It doesn't necessarily mean I feel left out. In fact, many times it allows me a different perspective on topics and issues that would otherwise go unseen.

&nbsp;

But I am also the villains. Plural. I am half Japanese and half White. In the progressive API spaces an emphasis is given to non-East Asians, which is outside the scope of this essay but which I completely understand and fully support. I understand the under-representation and how the focus is given because it is needed. However, even among East Asians, the Japanese are not exactly viewed in the best light. History classes dating back to when I first started taking history classes have taught me how Japan, at one time or another, has basically raped and pillaged all of Asia, and most recently even fought against the USA in World War II. Not exactly new information, I know, but it's kind of a double-whammy. I spend time in these Asian American spaces and the Japanese have had brutal conflicts with both Asia <i>and</i> America. And speaking of double-whammies, I'm also half White, and there doesn't really need to be any introduction or context as to why White people are villains. Groups like <b>hardboiled </b>essentially exist <i>because</i> of the White man. White privilege has become an oft-used term to describe the power held by Whites over practically everyone else. Subsequently there's a sort of externally assigned guilt that goes along with that, something I was made particularly aware of last semester when I learned that if you follow my lineage back far enough, you'll eventually reach slave owners. Yes, this is the hardboiled blog and I'm publicly admitting to being the great great great great great great grandson of slave owners. Because why not? It's not something I'm proud of, but it is what it is.

&nbsp;

So yes, I'm half White, but does that mean I enjoy White privilege? Perhaps. I grew up in a predominantly White community. Maybe that comes with privileges, but at that SASC meeting I realized that though I grew up in that predominantly White community, I was still always just a short Asian kid. When I really think about it, that's how people would identified me (I was also short). I had a generic hair cut. I was good at math. In the sixth grade I was cast in the play as the nerdy kid whose only lines were incomprehensible mash-ups of arbitrary math terms (“If my calculations are correct, the hypotenuse of the blah blah”). Sure, I'll make jokes about how great it is to be White, but in reality I know that I'll never actually <i>be White</i>. For instance, I'd never fit in at an all-White country club. Not that I'd ever want to, but my point is that it would never be an option. Again, I'd never want to. I can't stress that enough. Maybe that wasn't the greatest example. Still.

&nbsp;

Here's a better example: last week, I was talking to a friend that happens to be White. I mentioned my dad, and his immediate reply was “Oh, is he like, an <i>Asian</i> dad?” No, he is White. My dad is White. He is not an Asian dad. For some reason White people just think I'm full Asian. So, yeah, again, the country club isn't really an option. Continuing on.

&nbsp;

All of this is so odd because the White ethnicity is the recessive ethnicity. When someone is half White, half something else, they are almost always identified by the 'something else'. When someone asks me “what are you?” (the wording of which can be annoying in its own right), I usually respond with “half Japanese,” and usually that is enough. Maybe that doesn't seem like a big deal, but it certainly goes a long way towards showing where I really stand.

&nbsp;

In the end I'm not really sure what any of it means. I feel there should be an insightful moral or conclusion after something like this, but I've never thought about these aspects of my life as much as I have since I started spending time with <b>hardboiled</b>. So I guess that's why I'm here, writing this, figuring everything out.
